data.question:
Which matrix multiplication approach is most cache-efficient for large matrices in Java?

Options:
A) Naive triple-nested loop
B) Transposing the second matrix first
C) Using Java Streams
D) Leveraging `Arrays.parallelSetAll`

Code:
int[][] A = new int[1000][1000];
int[][] B = new int[1000][1000];
// ... Initialize matrices ...

data.explanation:
Title: Cache-Efficient Matrix Multiplication

Transposing the second matrix improves spatial locality by accessing contiguous memory.
Naive loops cause cache misses due to row-column access patterns.

Example 1:
// Naive O(n¬≥) approach
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
  for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)
    for (int k = 0; k < n; k++)
      C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j]; // Poor cache performance

Example 2:
// Transposed B
int[][] BT = transpose(B);
for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
  for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)
    for (int k = 0; k < n; k++)
      C[i][j] += A[i][k] * BT[j][k]; // Better cache hits

Example 3:
// Parallelized (but still inefficient without transposition)
Arrays.parallelSetAll(C, i -> {
  for (int j = 0; j < n; j++)
    for (int k = 0; k < n; k++)
      C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j];
  return C[i];
});

